[[Image:Academic Earth.png|250px|thumb]] '''Academic Earth''' is a website launched on March 24, 2009, by Richard Ludlow and co-founders Chris Bruner and Liam Pisano,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS157269+24-Mar-2009+PRN20090324 |title=Academic Earth Launches Website Offering Free Video Lectures from Leading Universities |date=March 24, 2009 |publisher=''[[Reuters]]'' |accessdate=2009-08-22 }}</ref><ref name=hulued>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/03/24/AR2009032400958.html |title=Academic Earth Is The Hulu For Education |accessdate=2009-03-26 | work=The Washington Post | first=Leena | last=Rao | date=2009-03-24}}</ref> which offers free [[online video lecture|online video courses and academic lecture]]s from the world's top universities such as [[UC Berkeley]], [[UCLA]], [[University of Michigan]], [[University of Oxford]] [[Harvard]], [[MIT]], [[Princeton University|Princeton]], [[Stanford]], and [[Yale|Yale.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://academicearth.org/universities/ |title=Academic Earth: Universities |accessdate=2009-03-26 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090331102234/http://www.academicearth.org/universities/| archivedate= 31 March 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> It is considered a search engine for full-text scholarly information, with video courses covering around 50 primary subject disciplines<ref>{{Cite book|title=Scholarly Information Discovery in the Networked Academic Learning Environment|last=Li|first=Lili|publisher=Chandos Publishing|year=2014|isbn=9781843347637|location=Oxford|pages=179}}</ref> ranging from [[Graphic design|Arts and Design]], [[Astronomy]], [[Biology]], [[Chemistry]], [[Computer Science]], [[Economics]], [[Engineering]], [[English literature|English]], [[Entrepreneurship]], [[History]], [[Humanities]], [[Law]], [[Mathematics]], [[Medicine]], [[Philosophy]], [[Physics]], [[Political Science]], [[Psychology]], [[Religion]], and [[Statistics]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://academicearth.org/subjects/ |title=Academic Earth: Subjects |accessdate=2009-03-26 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090328224809/http://www.academicearth.org/subjects |archivedate=2009-03-28 }}</ref>
==History== The idea behind Academic Earth came to Ludlow upon stumbling on a full video course lecture from MIT Mathematics Professor Gilbert Strang. Doing further research, he found out that there are various academic resources online although these resources were scattered across different websites and in varying file formats. Patterned after [[Hulu]], Academic Earth serves as an easily accessible repository for online academic lectures.<ref name=hulued /> The platform is also likened to what Google was trying to do with its defunct [[Knol]] project,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/technology/technology/2009/02/how_to_go_to_harvard_for_free.html|title=How To Go to Harvard for Free|last=Manjoo|first=Farhad|date=2009-02-19|work=Slate|access-date=2018-09-27|language=en-US|issn=1091-2339}}</ref> which aggregated scholarly articles. It was launched two days before [[YouTube]] introduced its own YouTube EDU service.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Meconomy: How to Reinvent Ourselves for the Future of Work|last=Albers|first=Markus|publisher=epubli GmbH|year=2010|isbn=9783869318868|location=Berlin|pages=83}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://lifehacker.com/5185679/youtube-edu-brings-free-education-to-the-masses|title=YouTube EDU Brings Free Education to the Masses|last=Pash|first=Adam|work=Lifehacker|access-date=2018-09-27|language=en-US}}</ref>
The website also offers online courses but unlike their formal versions, Academic Earth only publishes sorted video courses and sends users to the academic institutions offering them if they wish to complete it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.tesol.org/academic-earth-free-education-for-all/|title=Academic Earth: Free Education for All|last=Arntsen|first=Tara|date=October 28, 2004|website=TESOL International Association|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-09-27}}</ref> Participants also have little interaction with educators and with each other.
On January 10, 2012, it was announced that Academic Earth has been acquired by [[Ampush]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ampushmedia.com/news.html|title=Ampush Media: News|accessdate=2012-01-26 }}</ref>
