{{Infobox award | name = Feynman Prize in Nanotechnology | description = Experimental and theoretical advancements in nanotechnology research | presenter = [[Foresight Institute]] | country = United States | year = 1993 | website = {{URL|www.foresight.org/prize}} }}
The '''Feynman Prize in Nanotechnology''' is an award given by the [[Foresight Institute]] for significant advances in [[nanotechnology]]. Two prizes are awarded annually, in the categories of experimental and theoretical work. There is also a separate [[Inducement prize contest|challenge award]] for making a nanoscale robotic arm and 8-bit [[Adder (electronics)|adder]].
== Overview == The Feynman Prize consists of annual prizes in experimental and theory categories, as well as a one-time [[Inducement prize contest|challenge award]]. They are awarded by the [[Foresight Institute]], a nanotechnology education organization. The prizes are named in honor of physicist [[Richard Feynman]], whose 1959 talk ''[[There's Plenty of Room at the Bottom]]'' is considered to have inspired and informed the start of the field of nanotechnology.<ref name=":3" />
The annual Feynman Prize in Nanotechnology is awarded for pioneering work in nanotechnology, towards the goal of constructing atomically precise products through molecular machine systems. Input on prize candidates comes from both Foresight Institute personnel, and outside academic and commercial organizations. The awardees are selected mainly by an annually changing body of former winners and other academics.<ref name=":3" /> The prize is considered prestigious,<ref name=":3" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Heinze|first=Thomas|last2=Shapira|first2=Philip|last3=Senker|first3=Jacqueline|last4=Kuhlmann|first4=Stefan|date=2007-01-01|title=Identifying creative research accomplishments: Methodology and results for nanotechnology and human genetics|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11192-007-0108-6|journal=Scientometrics|language=en|volume=70|issue=1|pages=125–152|doi=10.1007/s11192-007-0108-6|issn=0138-9130}}</ref> and authors of one study considered it to be reasonably representative of notable research in the parts of nanotechnology under its scope.<ref name=":3">{{Cite journal|last=Marcovich|first=Anne|last2=Shinn|first2=Terry|date=December 1, 2010|title=Socio/intellectual patterns in nanoscale research: Feynman Nanotechnology Prize laureates, 1993–2007|url=http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/pdf/10.1177/0539018410377581|journal=Social Science Information|volume=49|issue=4|pages=615–638|doi=10.1177/0539018410377581|via=}}</ref>
The seaprate Feynman Grand Prize is a $250,000 challenge award to the first persons to create both a nanoscale robotic arm capable of precise positional control, and a nanoscale 8-bit [[Adder (electronics)|adder]], conforming to given specifications. It is intended to stimulate the field of [[molecular nanotechnology]].<ref name=":4">{{Cite web|url=http://electroiq.com/blog/2004/10/diamandis-to-chair-feynman-grand-prize-committee/|title=Diamandis to chair Feynman Grand Prize committee {{!}} Solid State Technology|website=electroiq.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nicolau|first=D.E.|last2=Phillimore|first2=J.|last3=Cross|first3=R.|last4=Nicolau|first4=D.V|date=July 2000|title=Nanotechnology at the crossroads: the hard or the soft way?|url=http://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0026269200000367|journal=Microelectronics Journal|volume=31|issue=7|pages=611–616|doi=10.1016/s0026-2692(00)00036-7|issn=0026-2692|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Davidian|first=Ken|date=2005|title=Prize Competitions and NASA’s Centennial Challenges Program|url=http://sci.esa.int/Conferences/ILC2005/Manuscripts/DavidianK-01-DOC.pdf|dead-url=|journal=International Lunar Conference|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-05-18}}</ref>
== History == The Feynman Prize was instituted in the context of Foresight Institute co-founder [[K. Eric Drexler]]'s advocacy of funding for molecular manufacturing.<ref name=":3" /> The prize was first given in 1993. Before 1997, one prize was given biennially. From 1997 on, two prizes were given each year in theory and experimental categories.<ref name=":3" /> By awarding these prizes early in the history of the field, the prize increased awareness of nanotechnology and influenced its direction.<ref name="NewDim">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U-78AwAAQBAJ&q=%22Feynman%20prize%22%20OR%20%22Feynman%20nanotechnology%20prize%22|title=Toward a New Dimension: Exploring the Nanoscale|last=Marcovich|first=Anne|last2=Shinn|first2=Terry|date=2014|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=9780198714613|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>{{rp|60}}<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stallbaumer|first=Clayton|date=2016|title=From Longitude to Altitude: Inducement Prize Contests as Instruments of Public Policy in Science and Technology|url=http://illinoisjltp.com/journal/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/stallbaumer.pdf|journal=Journal of Law, Technology & Policy|volume=2006|issue=1|pages=117–158|via=University of Illinois|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name="Nano-Hype">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rTPkmNLs870C&pg=PA250|title=Nano-Hype: The Truth Behind the Nanotechnology Buzz|last=Berube|first=David M.|publisher=Prometheus Books|isbn=9781615922369|language=en}}</ref>
The Grand Prize was announced in 1995 at the Fourth Foresight Conference on Molecular Nanotechnology and was sponsored by [[James R. Von Ehr II|James Von Ehr]] and Marc Arnold.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stix|first=Gary|date=1996|title=Waiting for Breakthroughs|jstor=24989486|journal=Scientific American|volume=274|issue=4|pages=94–99}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H7wvDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA121|title=How to Make a Spaceship: A Band of Renegades, an Epic Race, and the Birth of Private Space Flight|last=Guthrie|first=Julian|date=2017-09-05|publisher=Penguin|isbn=9781101980491|language=en}}</ref> In 2004, [[X-Prize Foundation]] founder [[Peter Diamandis]] was selected to chair the Feynman Grand Prize committee.<ref name=":4" />
