'''Jacaranda Music''' is a non-profit organization founded by impresario Patrick Scott and conductor/organist Mark Alan Hilt. Jacaranda produces an annual classical music concert series, mostly of modern music and works written since 2000 as well as rare older classical music with potential interest for contemporary listeners. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jacarandamusic.org/program-history/ |title=Program History|publisher=Jacaranda |access-date=September 13, 2018}}</ref> Jacaranda has been based in [[Santa Monica]], California since 2003. In 2016, the series was named by ''[[L.A. Weekly]]'' as the Best Contemporary Classical Series.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Payne |first1=John |title=Best Contemporary Classical Series |url=https://www.laweekly.com/best-of/2016/music-and-nightlife/best-rapper-7407206 |website=Best of L.A. |publisher=L.A. Weekly |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref>
Throughout its 16 seasons, Jacaranda has presented the compositions of [[Philip Glass]], [[John Cage]], [[Olivier Messiaen]], [[Gustav Mahler]], [[Lou Harrison]], [[Dylan Mattingly]], [[Mark Grey]], [[Florence Price]], [[Lukas Foss]], [[Julius Eastman]], [[Frederic Rzewski]], [[David Lang (composer)|David Lang]], [[Peter Maxwell Davies]], [[Horatiu Radulescu]], [[Franz Liszt]] and [[George Enescu]], among many others. Musicians have included [[Grammy]] and [[Emmy]] winner [[Gloria Cheng]], [[Anonymous 4]], Quatuor Diotima, Scott Dunn, [[Kathleen Supové]], [[Christopher Taylor (pianist)|Christopher Taylor]], and [[Billy Childs]]. Jacaranda's concerts have been reviewed by several publications, including the [[LA Times]], [[Classical Voice North America]], and [[BBC Music Magazine]]. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jacarandamusic.org/news/ |title=News|publisher=Jacaranda |access-date=September 13, 2018}}</ref> In 2018, The ''San Francisco Classical Voice'' said of Jacaranda: "To actually curate a concert is an art. It is one of the qualities that sets apart the Los Angeles music series Jacaranda. For more than 10 years… Jacaranda's concerts have been conceived as musical journeys of discovery…."<ref>{{cite web |last1=Farber |first1=Jim |title=A Flock of Oiseaux exotiques Reveals Jacaranda's Charms |url=https://www.sfcv.org/reviews/jacaranda/a-flock-of-oiseaux-exotiques-reveals-jacarandas-charms |website=San Francisco Classical Voice |publisher=San Francisco Classical Voice |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref> The ''[[LA Times]]'' has said of Jacaranda that it "is known for imaginative programs of challenging contemporary music."<ref>{{cite web |last1=Schultz |first1=Rick |title=15 ways to hear chamber music magic in L.A. this spring |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/la-ca-cm-spring-preview-chamber-20180325-htmlstory.html |website=Los Angeles Times |publisher=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref>
''Los Angeles Times'' music critic Mark Swed said of Jacaranda in 2013, "With demanding pieces by [[Péter Eötvös|Eötvös]] and the famed late Hungarian composer [[György Ligeti]], "Fierce Beauty" was the most ambitious undertaking so far and by far for Jacaranda.…With this concert, Jacaranda grew up, moving beyond local to national significance."<ref>{{cite web |last1=Swed |first1=Mark |title=Review: Jacaranda gives an important concert featuring Peter Eotvos |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/jan/14/entertainment/la-et-cm-jacaranda-etvs-review-20130114 |website=Los Angeles Times |publisher=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref>
The former dean of American music critics [[Alan Rich]] regularly wrote about Jacaranda, saying that they produce, "a kind of personalized programming so that you leave each event with the sense of having visited some very smart programming."<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rich |first1=Alan |title=DUTCH TREAT: SPHERES AND COOKIES |url=http://www.soiveheard.com/ |website=So I've Heard |publisher=Alan Rich |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref>
Since 2011, the Lyris Quartet has been its resident ensemble.
